title: The UK’s a ‘weak country’ as the government considers increasing asylum seeker payments
description: Reform UK Councillor Darren Grimes calls out UK Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood after she says increasing asylum seeker payments is “value for money”.  “Who exactly is it value for? It ain't the British public who are increasingly unsafe, It ain't the British taxpayer who is funding this madness,” Mr Grimes told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “We are a weak country … It’s absurd!”

title: ‘£200 million disgrace’ of an enquiry into the UK’s COVID-19 response
description: Reform UK Councillor Darren Grimes mocks the enquiry into the UK’s COVID-19 response as a “£200 million disgrace”.  “We ought to of gone faster, harder, longer. Right, that’s exactly what they've concluded,” Mr Grimes told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  ​“£200 million to tell us we should of locked down even faster.”

title: ‘Smart move’: Newly elected Kellie Sloane must project herself as a ‘teal’
description: Sky News Contributor Joe Hildebrand says as a “moderate Liberal”, NSW Liberal Leader Kellie Sloane has to project that she’s a “teal”.  Mr Hildebrand told Sky News host Steve Price, the New South Wales government is “pro-action” on climate change.  “It’s a very smart move … this is the nature of the party.” ​

title: Kellie Sloane’s appointment as NSW Liberal Leader ‘had to happen’
description: Former NSW Police minister David Elliott says incoming NSW Liberal Leader Kellie Sloane’s appointment “had to happen”.  Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio that Kellie Sloane will be a “fresh start” for the party.  “She’ll need to surround herself with the right people and a good team.”

title: Kellie Sloane must find ‘issues of difference’ from Labor
description: NSW Independent MP Tania Mihailuk says it will be “hard” for the incoming NSW Liberal Leader Kellie Sloane to compete with NSW Premier Chris Minns.  Ms Mihailuk said Kellie Sloane will need to “find issues of difference”.  “So far, the Liberals have been working with the Greens.”

title: Betting agencies ‘aggressively’ target young men
description: GT Communications’ Gemma Tognini says the betting industry “aggressively” targets young people.  “Young men, late teenagers and early 20s… a lot of them have betting apps on their phone,” Ms Tognini told Sky News host Steve Price.  “To me, it’s a bit of a head explosion; it’s just something we didn't do in my generation. “It is cause for concern.”

title: ABC ‘running for cover’ from its own gambling scandal
description: Sky News Contributor Joe Hildebrand recalls ABC’s “last flirtation” with online bidding, where a Four Corners reporter was doing a “side project” with an interviewee funded by a  “mysterious gambling company”.  “Gambling is legal  … I don't understand why there would be the slightest problem with it,” Mr Hildebrand told Sky News host Steve Price.  “I think this is the ABC running for cover from its own stuff of up with the young man on the street from Four Corners.”

title: Farmers revolt against battery projects
description: Dairy Farmer Craig McWhinney discusses how farmers are revolting against battery storage plants on farm land.

title: Chris Bowen ‘stuffing up’ Australia’s energy policy
description: Sky News host Steve Price says Chris Bowen is “stuffing up” energy policy in Australia.  Climate Change and Energy Minister Chris Bowen is set to serve as the COP31 president.  Australia has conceded defeat to Turkey to host the summit in 2026.

title: Australia has ‘dodged a bullet’ by not hosting the COP31 summit
description: The Australian’s Foreign Editor Graham Lloyd says Australia has “dodged a bullet” by not hosting the COP31 summit.  Climate Change and Energy Minister Chris Bowen is set to serve as the COP31 president.  Australia has conceded defeat to Turkey to host the summit in 2026.

title: ‘Outrageous’: Bowen and almost 500 representatives jet to COP30
description: One Nation leader Pauline Hanson says it's “outrageous” that the Minister for Climate Change and Energy Chris Bowen went to COP30 in Brazil with “496” representatives, including himself.  “These people who should not have been there at the cost to the taxpayer, it is just absolutely ridiculous,” Ms Hanson told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “He’s still spreading his rubbish … we have to throw out the Labor government.”

title: ‘Secretary’ Bowen serving in negotiating role to prepare his ‘exit strategy’
description: Former speaker of the house Bronwyn Bishop says Minister for Climate Change and Energy Chris Bowen is serving as COP31 president to prepare his “exit strategy”.  “He will spend his time overseas because that's where he wants to be when her gets out of parliament,” Ms Bishop told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “He’ll be a secretary.”

title: ‘Women everywhere’ in the Liberal Party now
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio discusses the perceived “woman problem” in the Liberal Party.  Ms De Giorgio said the NSW Liberal Leader is now Kellie Sloane.  “How can you say there’s a woman problem, when there’s women everywhere now.”

title: ‘Division’: People trying to ‘big note’ themselves by accusing Liberals of a women problem
description: Former NSW Police minister David Elliott says the people accusing the Liberal Party of having a woman problem are the ones trying to “big note themselves”.  Mr Elliott told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio that they are also trying to create some sort of “nonexistence division”.  “You can’t collectively say everybody in the Liberal Party has a problem with women.”

title: Adelaide University deputy vice chancellor ‘suddenly resigned’ after controversial comments
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio discusses a story from Adelaide University which “baffled” her.  Ms De Giorgio said the Adelaide University deputy vice chancellor has resigned weeks after she claimed people working from home on Friday and Monday were getting “four day weekends”.  “Workers were outraged … and now she’s suddenly resigned, she’s gone.”
